{"title_page": "David Vadiveloo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=May 2018}}\n{{lead too short|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      = David Selvarajah Vadiveloo\n| honorific_suffix          = \n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| image                     = David_Vadiveloo.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                = <!-- {{Birth date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place               = \n| disappeared_date          = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place         = \n| disappeared_status        = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| body_discovered           = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 = \n| nationality               = Australian\n| other_names               = \n| ethnicity                 = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| citizenship               = \n| education                 = Bachelor of Law, Bachelor of Arts, Grad. Dip. Film & Television\n| alma_mater                = Monash University, Victorian College of the Arts\n| occupation                = Lawyer, Human rights & Education consultant, Screen Producer\n| years_active              = \n| employer                  = Community Prophets Pty Ltd\n| organization              = \n| agent                     = \n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| influences                = \n| influenced                = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| net_worth                 = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height                    = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight                    = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| television                = \n| title                     = \n| term                      = \n| predecessor               = \n| successor                 = \n| party                     = \n| movement                  = \n| opponents                 = \n| boards                    = \n| religion                  = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| denomination              = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| criminal_charge           = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty          = \n| criminal_status           = \n| spouse                    = Rachel Naninaaq Edwardson\n| partner                   = \n| children                  = 3\n| parents                   = Victor and Anne Vadiveloo\n| relatives                 = \n| callsign                  = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| module                    = \n| module2                   = \n| module3                   = \n| module4                   = \n| module5                   = \n| module6                   = \n| website                   = <!-- {{URL|www.communityprophets.com}} -->\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n'''David Selvarajah Vadiveloo''' is an Australian lawyer, human rights and education consultant, cultural broker and screen producer.\n\nVadiveloo received the 2005 [[Australian Human Rights Commission]] Award for Individual Community Achievement and was the youngest person to be Highly Commended for the Australian [[Human Rights Medal (Australia)|Human Rights Medal]], recognising lifelong commitment and achievements in human rights.<ref name=\"hreoc1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hreoc.gov.au/about/media/media_releases/2005/67_05.html |title=2005 Human Rights Medal awarded to disability rights quiet achiever Kevin Cocks |publisher=Hreoc.gov.au |date=9 December 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> Vadiveloo is the Founder and Executive Director of the social justice, media and education agency Community Prophets. He leads the cultural safety and culturally responsive practice reform underway in schools that operate in Victoria's juvenile justice system<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parkvillecollege.vic.edu.au/?p=1343 |title=NAIDOC 2016 at Parkville |date=20 July 2016 |website=parkvillecollege.vic.edu.au |publisher=Parkville College |accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> and consults to high-profile Indigenous community and commercial organisations in Australia and the United States including the Mirarr Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mirarr.net/news_items/abc-david-vadiveloo-dicusses-the-ranger-spill |title=ABC: David Vadiveloo dicusses the Ranger spill |date=12 December 2013 |website=mirarr.net |publisher=Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation |accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> and the [[Inupiat]] Education Department<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nsbsd.org/domain/44 |title=I\u00f1upiaq Education |website=nsbsd.org |publisher=The North Slope Borough School District |accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> in Alaska. Vadiveloo's social justice films have been nominated for [[Australian Film Institute Awards]] in both the drama and documentary categories.\n\nVadiveloo is married to [[Inupiat]] screen producer, education consultant and cultural broker Rachel Naninaaq Ewardson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nativenetworks.si.edu/eng/rose/edwardson_r.htm |title=Rachel Naninaaq Edwardson \u2013 Native Networks |publisher=Nativenetworks.si.edu |date= |accessdate=1 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911034224/http://nativenetworks.si.edu/eng/rose/edwardson_r.htm |archive-date=11 September 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nVadiveloo was born in [[Wagga Wagga]], Australia, to a Tamil father and Anglo-Celtic mother. He holds a [[Bachelor of Laws]] and Bachelor of Arts from [[Monash University]], Melbourne, Australia and a [[Graduate Diploma]] in Film and Television from the [[Victorian College of the Arts]] at [[University of Melbourne]], Australia.\n\n==Awards==\nVadiveloo's work in human rights, media and culturally responsive education saw him awarded the 2005 [[Australian Human Rights Commission]] Award for Individual Community Achievement, specifically for his work with Indigenous and marginalised peoples.<ref name=\"hreoc2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hreoc.gov.au/about/media/media_releases/2005/68_05.html |title=Community Awards go to ChilOut and David Vadiveloo |publisher=Hreoc.gov.au |date=9 December 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref> In 2005 he was also the youngest person to be Highly Commended for the Australian [[Human Rights Medal (Australia)|Human Rights Medal]], recognising lifelong commitment and achievements in human rights.<ref name=\"hreoc1\"/>\nVadiveloo's films and interactive screenworks have received numerous nominations and awards including the 2002 Canadian Golden Sheaf Award for Best International Documentary,<ref name=\"goldensheafawards1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.goldensheafawards.com/files/File/winners/winners2002.html |title=Canada's Golden Sheaf Awards |publisher=Goldensheafawards.com |accessdate=1 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904171945/http://www.goldensheafawards.com/files/File/winners/winners2002.html |archive-date=4 September 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the 2005 [[Australian Interactive Media Industry Association]] Award for Best Interactive Learning<ref name=\"aimia1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aimia.com.au/home/awards/aimia-awards/hall-of-fame/12th-aimia-awards/12th-awards-winners |title=AIMIA 12th Awards Winners |publisher=Aimia.com.au |accessdate=1 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130506225206/http://aimia.com.au/home/awards/aimia-awards/hall-of-fame/12th-aimia-awards/12th-awards-winners |archive-date=6 May 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and 2009 [[Australian Film Institute]] nominations in both Drama and Documentary.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=7854&Section=Non_Feature_Nominees_Production_Information#ShortFiction |title=The Australian Film Institute &#124; Non Feature Film Nominees: Production Information |publisher=Afi.org.au |accessdate=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322074712/http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=7854&Section=Non_Feature_Nominees_Production_Information#ShortFiction |archive-date=22 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"afi2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=9052&Section=Documentary_Nominees_Production_Info |title=The Australian Film Institute &#124; Documentary Nominees \u2013 Production Info |publisher=Afi.org.au |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120217025951/http://www.afi.org.au/AM/ContentManagerNet/HTMLDisplay.aspx?ContentID=9052&Section=Documentary_Nominees_Production_Info |archive-date=17 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Legal and Human Rights career===\nVadiveloo began work as a solicitor and [[barrister]] in the Northern Territory of Australia in 1994. He worked on the successful Central Land Council [[Native Title]] Application, Hayes v Northern Territory,<ref>Hayes v Northern Territory (1999) 97 FCR 32</ref> brought by the [[Arrernte people|Arrernte]] people of the Alice Springs region.\n\nIn 1996, Vadiveloo was a policy advisor to the Federal Race Discrimination Commissioner of the [[Australian Human Rights Commission]]. He facilitated national community consultations with Indigenous and Culturally And Linguistically Diverse (CALD) communities about the operation and effectiveness of the Australian [[Racial Discrimination Act]]. His consultations formed the basis of the 1996 State of the Nation Report.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrights.gov.au/racial%5Fdiscrimination/report/state_nation.html |title=State of the Nation 1996 &#124; Australian Human Rights Commission |publisher=Humanrights.gov.au |date= |accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2001 and 2003 Vadiveloo worked alongside former [[Australian Human Rights Commission]]er Chris Sidoti and Bill Barker, former Director of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade's Human Rights and Indigenous Issues section <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dtp.unsw.edu.au/mr-bill-barker|title=Mr Bill Barker|website=dtp.unsw.edu.au|publisher=University of New South Wales|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> as a trainer in the Australia-Indonesia Specialised Training Project II,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.monash.edu/law/centres/castancentre/training-and-consultancy/indo-2002|title=Indonesia-Australia Specialised Training Project Phase II|website=monash.edu|publisher=Monash University|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> facilitating human rights training programs with Indonesian NGO's, military and government employees in areas of race discrimination, torture and conflict resolution.\n\nSince 2007, Vadiveloo and wife Rachel Naninaaq Edwardson have facilitated culturally responsive practice and social justice media programs in partnership with Indigenous and marginalised youth in the [[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[New South Wales|NSW]] and [[Alaska]].<ref>[http://www.creativespaces.net.au/artists/579/david-vadiveloo/ DAVID VADIVELOO] Retrieved on 8 Feb 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.roninfilms.com.au/person/3008/david-vadiveloo.html/ David Vadiveloo] Retrieved on 8 Feb 2018</ref> Their program in Cape York became the subject of the 2-part ABC Television documentary Voices From the Cape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s2496801.htm|title=Message Stick: Voices from the Cape - Part 1|date=22 February 2009|website=abc.net.au|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 at the request of the New South Wales Legal Aid Commission Vadiveloo and Edwardson devised and facilitated the Burn project with marginalised youth from linguistically and culturally diverse backgrounds in inner-city Sydney. The 6-month project was a crime prevention initiative that resulted in the production of the [[Australian Film Institute]] nominated Burn film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://burn-movie.com.au/|title=Welcome to Burn|website=burn-movie.com.au|publisher=Legal Aid NSW|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Vadiveloo was Acting Chief Executive Officer of the Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation.<ref name=\"Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mirarr.net/gac.html |title=Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation |publisher=Mirarr.net |date= |accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> On behalf of the Corporation he drafted the landmark research agreement<ref>{{cite news |author=Tony Wright |date=20 July 2017 |title=Aboriginal archaeological discovery in Kakadu rewrites the history of Australia |url=https://www.theguardian.com.au/story/4801721/astounding-discovery-in-a-rock-shelter-rewrites-australias-history/?cs=7 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=14 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180410072027/https://www.theguardian.com.au/story/4801721/astounding-discovery-in-a-rock-shelter-rewrites-australias-history/?cs=7 |archive-date=10 April 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> used for the [[Madjedbebe]] archaeological excavation which has changed the scientifically accepted date of modern human occupation in Australia.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Helen Davidson |author2=Calla Walhquist |date=20 July 2017 |title=Australian dig finds evidence of Aboriginal habitation up to 80,000 years ago |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/jul/19/dig-finds-evidence-of-aboriginal-habitation-up-to-80000-years-ago |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref> Vadiveloo continues his work as a consultant to the Gundjeihmi Aboriginal Corporation today.\n\nIn 2015 Vadiveloo and Edwardson devised and facilitated a culturally responsive education pilot program for youth in custody at the Parkville Youth Justice Facility in Melbourne, Australia. The program included a number of profile artists including [[Archie Roach]], [[Radical Son]] and Abdul Abdullah.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abdulabdullah.com/home.html|title=Abdul Abdullah|website=abdulabdullah.com|accessdate=19 June 2017}}</ref> and resulted in Vadiveloo leading the cultural safety and culturally responsive practice reform that is being implemented in all schools in youth justice facilities in the State of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]].\n\n===Film career===\nIn 1998, after completing the Victorian College of the Arts Film and Television post-graduate degree, Vadiveloo returned to Alice Springs and established a media program at the Irrkerlantye Learning Centre, working with [[Aboriginal Australian|Aboriginal]] children from the [[Alice Springs Town Camps|Town Camps of Alice Springs]] and re-engaging them with schooling through media.,<ref name=\"flowtv651\">{{cite web|url=http://flowtv.org/?p=651 |title=Rethinking the Digital Age &#124; Flow |publisher=Flowtv.org |date=21 January 2005 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nVadiveloo's documentary ''Trespass'' (2002), about the [[Mirrar]] leader [[Yvonne Margarula]] and her battle to stop the [[Jabiluka]] mine site, won multiple awards<ref name=\"goldensheafawards1\"/> and his documentary Beyond Sorry (2004) about Australia's [[Stolen Generations]] premiered on Australia's [[ABC Television]] and was a festival favourite at the 2004 [[Sydney Film Festival]].\n\nVadiveloo directed and co-produced ''Us Mob'' (2005), the first Aboriginal children's television series in Australia and the first interactive Indigenous television series in the world.\n\nTwo films written and directed by Vadiveloo were nominated at the [[2009 Australian Film Institute Awards]]: the half-hour crime drama ''Burn'' (created with at-risk inner city youth) was nominated for Best Short Fiction Film and Voices from the Cape (which documented a program run by his company Community Prophets in the Aboriginal community of [[Aurukun]] in [[Cape York Peninsula|Cape York]], Australia) was nominated for best documentary series. Vadiveloo received Best Director nominations for both films at the Australian Directors Guild Awards in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adg.org.au/uploads/media-library/201008/2010%20nominees.pdf |title=Australian Directors Guild |publisher=ADG |accessdate=1 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130410040815/http://adg.org.au/uploads/media-library/201008/2010%20nominees.pdf |archivedate=10 April 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nVadiveloo founded the social justice, media and education agency Community Prophets in 2005. The company facilitates culturally responsive practice reform and produces and teaches film and television in partnership with marginalised communities.\n\n==Filmography==\n*2012 ''Project Chariot'' \u2013 Producer, Editor (Dir: Rachel Naninaaq Edwardson) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaskapublic.org/2012/10/09/project-chariot-documentary-premiere/|title=Project Chariot Documentary Premiere|last=Museum|first=Anchorage|date=2012-10-09|website=Alaska Public Media|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*2012 ''Songline to Happiness'' \u2013 Producer (Dir: Danny Teece-Johnson) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://metroscreen.org.au/songline-to-happiness-wins-at-imaginenative-festival/|title=Songline to Happiness wins at ImagineNATIVE Festival|last=metroscreen|website=Metro Screen|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*2009 ''The Voice of our Spirit'' \u2013 Editor (Dir: Rachel Naninaaq Edwardson) <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://filmcatalog.nmai.si.edu/title/2052/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=8 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408214006/http://filmcatalog.nmai.si.edu/title/2052/ |archive-date=8 April 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*2008 ''Voices from the Cape'' \u2013 Writer, Director, co-Producer <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voicesfromthecape.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-04-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140125150738/http://voicesfromthecape.com/ |archivedate=25 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[http://www.voicesfromthecape.com.au]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>\n*2008 ''Burn'' \u2013 Writer, Director <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://burn-movie.com.au/|title=Burn|website=burn-movie.com.au|language=en|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burn-movie.com.au |title=Burn |publisher=Burn-movie.com.au |date=3 July 2012 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n*2005 ''Us Mob'' \u2013 Writer, Director, co-Producer <ref>http://www.abc.net.au/usmob/</ref>\n*2004 ''Beyond Sorry'' \u2013 Writer, Director, Producer <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/6572/beyond-sorry-from-caama-collection.html|title=BEYOND SORRY [from the CAAMA Collection] - Ronin Films - Educational DVD Sales|last=Internet|first=Chirp|website=www.roninfilms.com.au|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://australianscreen.com.au/titles/beyond-sorry/ |title=Video Overview Beyond Sorry (2003) on ASO \u2013 Australia's audio and visual heritage online |publisher=Australianscreen.com.au |date= |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/guide/netw/200705/programs/ZY7504A001D1052007T233500.htm |title=ABC TV Guide |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=1 May 2007 |accessdate=7 July 2012}}</ref>\n*2002 ''Bush Bikes'' \u2013 Writer, Director, Producer<ref>{{Citation|title=Bush Bikes|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0386348/|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*2002 ''Jabiru 0886: Trespass'' Writer, Director, co-Producer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.roninfilms.com.au/feature/6588/jabiru-0886-trespass-from-caama-collection.html|title=JABIRU 0886: TRESPASS [from the CAAMA Collection] - Ronin Films - Educational DVD Sales|last=Internet|first=Chirp|website=www.roninfilms.com.au|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>\n*2001 ''Tales from a suitcase series 2'' - Writer, Director<ref name=\"screen\">[https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/p/david-vadiveloo/22404/ David Vadiveloo] Retrieved on 8 Feb 2018</ref>\n*2001 ''Trespass'' - Director, Producer <ref name=\"screen\"/>\n*1999 ''Iwerre Atherrame'' - Writer, Director<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/iwerre-atherrame-two-paths/oclc/222921036 |title=Iwerre atherrame = two paths. |website=worldcat.org |publisher=OCLC |accessdate=14 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Vadiveloo, David (2007). \"A time for empowerment or a new digital divide? \" in da Rimini, Francesca and d/Lux/MediaArts \"A Handbook for Coding Cultures\" (2007)\n*Ginsburg, Faye (2006) \"Rethinking the Digital Age\" in Toynbee, Jason & Hesmondhalgh, David (2008) \"The media and social theory\" p136\n\n==References==\n{{cleanup|section|reason=The inline references need to be put in the article|date=June 2012}}\n\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2005/s1319739.htm |title=Stateline Northern Territory |publisher=Abc.net.au |accessdate=7 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110122507/http://www.abc.net.au/stateline/nt/content/2005/s1319739.htm |archive-date=10 November 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<ref>[http://